<dl id="n36152b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36152b">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36152b"> 152(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> mixed community / expires 35 cubic <font color="green">[mete]</font> / feet <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>of carbonic acid<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> per night / 24000 cubic feet of / air needed</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Now let us contrast the amount of air space provided in the houses of the 4705 overcrowded persons in York with that which authorities consider necessary for the maintenance of health. In Messrs. Notter and Firth&apos;s standard work, <cite>The Theory and Practice of Hygiene</cite>, the question of air space required for health purposes is fully discussed. They point out that although the <mark>amount of carbonic acid gas expired by different individuals at different times is not constant</mark>, &ldquo;We shall not be far from the probable truth if we adopt the following amounts of carbonic acid gas as being evolved during repose:&mdash; <br>Adult males &hellip; 0.72 of a <mark>cubic foot per hour</mark>. &hellip; <br>Under those conditions the amount of fresh air to be supplied in health during repose ought to be:&mdash; <br>For adult males <mark>3600 cubic feet per head per hour = 120 cub. metres</mark>. <small> B. Seebohm Rowntree, <a name="BSRP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BSRP"><cite title="source">Poverty, A Study of Town Life</cite></a>, 3rd ed.? (1922) 208</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
